On 12/13/04 9:15 PM, "Tom Shinn" <turtlebus(-at-)msn.com> wrote:

> 2. WHat happens if the lead is extended beyond the prescribed length? Does the
> reading go up or down? Will the guage still work in a linear fashion?

It shouldn't have an effect according to the 2nd Seebeck law:
 
> In a circuit as shown consisting of two dissimilar metals with their junctions
> at temperatures T1 and T2, a third metal is introduced by cutting and forming
> two junctions as shown.

http://www.nphheaters.com/technical/images/thermo3.gif

> If the temperature of the third metal introduced is
> uniform over its entire length, the total electromotive force will be
> unaffected. As a consequence of this law any measuring device or lead wire can
> be added to the circuit without affecting the accuracy as long as the new
> junctions are at the same temperature. This law also permits soldering or
> brazing of thermocouple junctions.

